# Testing Conventions

## Mocking Supabase chainable queries

Each method in the chain must return the chain object. Only the terminal method resolves:

```ts
const node: Record<string, unknown> = {};
["select", "in", "update"].forEach((m) => { node[m] = vi.fn().mockReturnValue(node); });
node.eq = vi.fn().mockResolvedValue({ data: [...], error: null });
```

If a route calls `.insert().select().single()`, each must be chained — `insert` returns an object with `select`, which returns an object with `single`.

## Hoisted mocks

Use `vi.hoisted` when a mock variable is referenced inside a `vi.mock` factory to avoid "cannot access before initialization":

```ts
const mockFn = vi.hoisted(() => vi.fn());
vi.mock("some-module", () => ({
  default: vi.fn().mockImplementation(function () { return { method: mockFn }; }),
}));
```

## Mocking `redirect` from `next/navigation`

`redirect` throws in real Next.js — mirror that so execution stops as expected:

```ts
vi.mock("next/navigation", () => ({
  redirect: vi.fn((url: string) => { throw new Error(`REDIRECT:${url}`); }),
}));
```

Assert with `rejects.toThrow("REDIRECT:/expected-path")`.

## Fixture completeness

Fixtures must include every field the route logic actually reads. A missing field (e.g. `on_demand`, `inventory`) silently evaluates as `undefined`, causing guards to never fire and producing false-green tests.
